{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"02288059-5206-48fc-829a-86c8b4bd5bc4","content":"The `src/MyMcpServer/` directory doesn't exist yet, so I'll give you the general guidance for packaging a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool.\n\n## Required `.csproj` Configuration\n\nAdd these properties to your project file:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n## Key properties explained\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g., `dotnet tool run my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType` | Must be `Exe` for tools |\n\n## Publishing steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n## User installation\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. No special MCP-specific packaging is needed — stdio transport \"just works\" since the tool is a regular console app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d61a335b-7e79-439d-8bd7-5c19fd9062e7","outputTokens":477,"requestId":"201B:35A1EF:1C1E2D0:1F289D6:6A052254"},"id":"09ae45c9-e322-4073-b7ef-0b6efbf21f42","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:16:14.206Z","parentId":"1f4a1891-2103-4c39-8f60-461c4954fd5e"}
